04927nam a22006015i 9780226808222DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021007617  a9780226808222  a(DE-B1597)590432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aHQ73b.V53 2021 4aHQ73b.V53 2021 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a306.762231 aVider, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Queerness of Home :bGender, Sexuality, and the Politics of Domesticity after World War II /cStephen Vider. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b57 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. The Politics and Performance of Home -- tONE. INTEGRATIONS -- tCHAPTER ONE. “Something of a Merit Badge”: Lesbian and Gay Marriage and Romantic Adjustment -- tCHAPTER TWO. “Oh Hell, May, Why Don’t You People Have a Cookbook?”: Camp Humor and Gay Domesticity -- tTWO. REVOLUTIONS -- tCHAPTER THREE. “The Ultimate Extension of Gay Community”: Communal Living, Gay Liberation, and the Reinvention of the Household -- tCHAPTER FOUR. “Fantasy Is the Beginning of Creation”: Imagining Lesbian Feminist Architecture -- tTHREE. REFORMS -- tCHAPTER FIVE. “Some Hearts Go Hungering”: Homelessness and the First Wave of LGBTQ Shelter Activism -- tCHAPTER SIX. “Picture a Coalition”: Community Caregiving and the Politics of HIV/AIDS at Home -- tEPILOGUE. The Futures of the Queer Home -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVider uncovers how LGBTQ people reshaped domestic life in the postwar United States. From the Stonewall riots in 1969 to the ACT UP protests of the 1980s and ’90s, histories of queer and trans politics have almost exclusively centered on public activism. In The Queerness of Home, Stephen Vider shifts the focus inward, showing that the intimacy of domestic space has been equally crucial to the history of postwar LGBTQ life. Beginning in the 1940s, LGBTQ activists looked more and more to the home as a site of connection, care, and cultural inclusion. Long portrayed as quintessential outsiders, LGBTQ people creatively reconfigured the American household to make room for their romantic and sexual relationships and communities. They struggled with the conventions of marriage, challenged the gendered codes of everyday acts like cooking, resisted isolation by reimagining the home’s architecture, and contested the racial and class boundaries of kinship and belonging through communes, shelters, and caregiving networks. Retelling LGBTQ history from the inside out, Vider reveals the surprising ways the home became, and remains, a charged site in battles for social and economic justice. LGBTQ people not only realized new forms of community and culture for themselves—they remade the possibilities of home life for everyone.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aDomestic relations. 0aSexual minoritiesxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aSexual minoritiesxSocial conditions. 0aSexual minorities' families. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahome, domesticity, privacy, LGBTQ, belonging, kinship, family, gender, sexuality, LGBTQ history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226808222423Coveruhttps://w